Bark.com — Trading Diagnostic

Prepared for: LCM Assessment (Feb 2026)  |  Data Period: July 2024 – December 2025  |  UK & US Markets  |  12 Categories × 3 Channels

Company Context

Bark.com is a London-headquartered services marketplace, founded in 2014, that connects consumers with local professionals across 1,000+ service categories. Its revenue model is lead-based: consumers submit project requests for free, Bark matches them to relevant professionals, and professionals pay per response (PPR) to access the lead. The company operates in 11 markets including the UK (its core market) and the US (its largest growth market), with approximately 265 employees and an estimated annual revenue of $50–100M.

The diagnostic below uses a comparable H2 window (Jul–Dec 2024 vs Jul–Dec 2025) as the primary time range, since it provides a clean year-over-year comparison and eliminates seasonality bias.

Part 1: UK Country Performance

Executive Summary: The UK business is experiencing a revenue and profit contraction despite growing traffic. H2 2025 revenue fell 16.7% YoY to £2.08M (from £2.50M), and profit declined 19.8% to £952K. The core challenge is a collapsing submission rate — sessions grew +9.4%, but submissions dropped -8.9%.

Diagnosis: The Funnel Is Breaking at the Top

Fig 2. UK Funnel Rate Shifts — Slope Graph (H2 2024 → H2 2025)
Fig 3. UK Q1 Pass Rate & Submission Rate — Monthly Trend
Key Insight: The Q1 Pass Rate collapsed -11.2pp (57.3% → 46.2%) — the single largest funnel leakage point. Over half of H2 2025 visitors abandon before answering the first question. Meanwhile, Q1→Submit rate actually improved from 51.1% to 52.9%, confirming the break is at the very top of the funnel.

Revenue per project is declining. Rev per released project fell from ~£9.16 to ~£8.54 (-6.8%), suggesting category mix shift or reduced professional willingness to pay.

Paid responses declined -21.4% — steeper than the submission decline (-8.9%), indicating supply-side pullback even among released projects.

Metrics to Prioritise

Primary: Submission Rate (and Q1 Pass Rate). A 1pp improvement yields ~10,800 additional submissions per half ≈ £80K–90K incremental revenue.

Secondary: Revenue per Released Project. Captures both professional engagement and category mix health.

Part 2: Marketing Channel Deep-Dive

Primary Concern: Channel 2 has scaled massively (+127.8% sessions) but delivers poor-quality traffic that is dragging down the entire UK business. ROAS has fallen to 1.28, approaching breakeven.

Why Channel 2 is the root cause: Ch2 Q1 pass rate fell from 45.7% to 30.3%. Given that Ch2 now represents ~35% of total sessions (up from ~17%), its poor conversion is mechanically diluting the blended UK submission rate by 4–5pp. Revenue per paid response also declined from £14.04 to £13.21 (-5.9%) — the only channel to fall.
Recommendation: Cap or reduce Channel 2 spend and reallocate budget to Channel 1. Conduct granular analysis of Channel 2 sub-sources. Invest in Channel 3 (SEO/content) for long-term margin improvement.

Structural demand decline: Volume collapsed across all channels (Ch1 halved from £922K → £451K). Seller disengagement accelerating — rev/project fell from £57 to £36, response rate from 95% to 78%. Web design is being commoditised by AI tools and no-code platforms.

Growth driver: Monetisation improvement, not just volume. Rev/project nearly doubled (£30 → £55), response rate rose from 68% to 83%. Spend grew only +30.2% vs revenue +113%. This is the playbook for healthy category growth: supply engagement → RPP growth.
